After all, it got its start on a wave of political instability when the Supreme Council for the Armed Forces (SCAF) took control of the country on 11 February 2011 from struggling President Hosni Mubarak, who was ousted only months before. This new authority issued law Number 77 nullifying the Mubarak regime’s constitution.

Perhaps this period could also not have existed without SCAF’s infamous law nowhere to be seen, under which hundreds of young protesters and government opponents languished in harsh prison conditions guarded by Central Security Forces (CSF) for months without legal charge and subject to torture.

This could also be told without the lingering question of where could all the money in Egyptian street rams be? Why would an unpoliced street bring in piles of greenbacks?
